  1. Best overall for semantic discovery (no exact keywords needed)
  Elicit (elicit.com) — My #1 recommendation for interns right now.
  You type a normal question in English (“What are new methods to improve CRISPR efficiency in plants?”) and it searches 125M+ papers using semantic similarity. It returns tables with methods, results,
  limitations — perfect for idea generation. It catches papers that Google Scholar would miss. Free tier is very generous.
  Semantic Scholar (semanticscholar.org) — Built by the Allen Institute for AI.
  Semantic search + AI-generated TL;DR summaries + citation graphs. Type your topic naturally and it finds relevant work even if wording differs. It indexes a huge number of international Chinese papers
  too. Bonus: “Highly Influential Citations” filter.
  Research Rabbit + Litmaps (both free) — Visual “maps” of papers.
  Paste one good paper (or your keywords) → it builds a network of 50–100 related papers. Amazing for discovering hidden gems you’d never keyword-search. Great for Chinese work that got cited
  internationally.
  SciSpace (scispace.com) — Great for explaining papers + semantic search.
  Ask questions and it pulls relevant sections from papers worldwide.
  R Discovery (app or web) — Newer AI tool that recommends papers based on your reading habits/topics. Uses semantic + personalization.
  These tools are way better than plain Google Scholar for your exact problem.

  2. Tools specifically for Chinese papers (the ones Western tools often miss)
  Chinese research is massive — China publishes more papers than any country in many fields (engineering, materials, AI, chemistry, biology, etc.). Here’s how to actually find them:

  CNKI (China National Knowledge Infrastructure) — The #1 database for Chinese papers.
  Go to oversea.cnki.net (English interface).
  You can search entirely in English — it translates and matches concepts. Covers journals, theses, conferences, patents. Many have English abstracts/full-text options.
  → Most universities give free access via library VPN/proxy (just search “[your university] CNKI” on their library site). If you’re in China or have access, this is gold.
  PubScholar (pubscholar.cn) — Completely free (from Chinese Academy of Sciences).
  Academic journals, preprints, patents, datasets. English search works well. Excellent for sciences/engineering.
  ChinaXiv (chinaxiv.org or via CNKI) — China’s national preprint server.
  For the absolute newest Chinese research (before it hits journals). Free and open.
  Pro tricks to find Chinese papers even in English tools:

  In Semantic Scholar or Google Scholar: add affiliation keywords like “Tsinghua University”, “Chinese Academy of Sciences”, “Zhejiang University”, or just “China” + your topic.
  Google Scholar settings → Languages → “Search for pages in any language” (this surfaces Chinese titles with English abstracts).
  Many top Chinese papers also appear on arXiv, ResearchGate, or international journals (Scopus/Web of Science) with full English versions.
