  Thought for 28s

  Yes — in simple terms:

  What they did

  They tried to solve this problem:

  “A robot can do a skill it already knows, but on a new object it never had robot demonstrations for.”

  Their idea was not to collect new robot demos for every new object.
  Instead, they took a normal VLA robot model and added a cheap second source of data:

  robot demonstration data for skills like move, push, rotate, bin-pick
  plus image-text data of many extra objects, where each object has a name and a bounding box in the image

  Then they connect those two worlds by making the robot model “reason” using the object name + location box before acting. So the model learns:

  what the object is called
  where it is in the image
  and how that should connect to an action

  That is the main trick of the paper.

  What is actually new

  The main new part is not a brand-new robot architecture.

  The new part is this training pipeline:

  take a VLA model,
  co-train it with robot data + image-text localization data,
  use bounding boxes as the bridge between language, vision, and action,
  and even adapt to a new object later using just a few smartphone photos and quick fine-tuning.

  So the paper’s core claim is:

  you do not need robot demonstrations for every new object, if you can teach the model the new object through cheap image-text grounding.

  Does it really work?

  Kind of yes — but only partially.

  According to their experiments, it clearly helps a lot compared with their baseline:

  On the simple “move to the object” task:
  base DiVLA on OOD objects: 8%
  their method without bounding boxes: 19%
  full ObjectVLA: 64% on 100 novel objects
  So the method seems to genuinely improve unseen-object recognition.
  On harder unseen-object tasks:
  Rotate OOD: 39/60
  Push OOD: 52/60
  Bin-picking OOD:
  OpenVLA: 17/150
  ObjectVLA: 87/150
  So it does better than the comparison model in their setup.
  For adding new objects with just smartphone photos:
  Pikachu: 80%
  toy cat: 90%
  after only 21 images per object and 1 epoch of continual training.
  But here is the important catch

  This is not “problem solved.”

  Why?

  Because the paper also shows the method is still fragile:

  64% on 100 OOD objects is good progress, but not robust enough to call solved
  many failures on harder tasks were due to execution, especially grasping/rotating unseen objects
  the experiments are still in a controlled lab setup
  they admit they struggle with new backgrounds and lighting
  the extra image-text data was collected by the authors, not from arbitrary internet images
  they have not shown strong transfer across big visual/domain gaps yet.
